\begin_layout Section
DATA
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We look at the consumption in Tanzania and compare it with South Africa
 - which may be more socially unequal but is an overall less poor country.
 A country like Tanzania is likely to have more economic inequality and
 less development of common services compared to South Africa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Descriptive statistics on the Tanzanian data are then presented.
 We focus on food expenditure - which is recorded with a greater level of
 detail than other expenditures.
 As market prices are recorded for food items, we check how the higher budget
 shares are associated with choice of higher price items.
 We find that the consumption of highest prices items doesn't always result
 in higher budget shares.
 Tea and coffee don't form the highest budget shares (while they are expensive).
 Items that are of high price and have low budget shares while have cheaper
 substitutes in the market do qualify for the expensive non-durable consumption
 criteria for quality.
 Other descriptive statistics measure, e.g.
 the skewnesss of total expenditure on the item can also hint whether only
 a small proportion of population gets to spend more on the item.
 Noticeably, the budget share on skin-cream etc.
 - which we may have normally associated with 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

visible
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 consumption - is quite low.
 The variance on the consumption of skin-cream is in fact lower than that
 for bread or milk.
 The budget shares for cigarettes seem quite high (and quite skewed) - however,
 since there are no cheaper substitutes available we don't consider cigarettes
 as part of status consumption.
 Although the descriptive statistics seem to confirm the heuristic that
 amongst many substitutable items, the distribution of expensive varieties
 is more likely to be skewed, it is worth emphasising that skewness or mean-cost
 - is not to be used as a criteria to pick items for status consumption.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
When comparing a developing economy with a developed economy, one would
 always find the consumption items in the developed world that have no equivalen
t in the developing country.
 For example, while comparing the Tanzanian data with the South African
 survey (IES), we do not find holiday expenses and car rental in the Tanzanian
 LSMS survey.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Further, the partition of certain categories is of particular significance
 to our analysis.
 The simple repackaging model requires that the quality variants of an item
 are perfect substitutes.
 We therefore make sure that only the variants of an item are grouped into
 perfect substitutes.
 In food, we put goat and meat in the same group - but not tea and coffee
 - because there is little sense in substituting.
 The categories are divided so that demand can be considered separable but
 and lumped together when they are closed substitutes.
 Instead of considering beef, pork and goat as varieties of meat - we lump
 them together as high price sources of protein - a step performed primarily
 to observe the effect of switching to pricier sources of protein (rather
 than pricier sources of meat).
 Similarly, when analysing holiday expenses in South African data (IES),
 we don't distinguish between expensive holidays and cheaper holidays -
 but count expenditure on holidays as expensive non-durable consumption
 under entertainment/personal-care.
 Instead of a cheaper holiday, we consider measure of the expenditure on
 holiday.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We refrain from using detailed price of assets purchased (available in the
 Tanzanian data for 2012) - since recording of assets is different in SA
 IES and TNZ LSMS surveys.
 More particularly, the expenditure on furniture and other assets is a diary
 expenditure in the SA IES data while the assets are recorded separately
 as a recall in the Tanzanian LSMS.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
While we are interested in studying the effect of ethnicity, but given the
 different make-up of the two countries, the data for ethnicity is not comaprabl
e either -SA IES records race, the LSMS records religion and native-language.
 The social identity data can thus only be only be used for studying segmentatio
n of demand within each economy.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Notice that the recall method is particularly volatile in a developing country
 where regular payment setups are hardly a norm.
 We must be careful therefore with interpreting differences in the budget
 share over snapshots (2008,2010 and 2012) for a particular household -
 as the household may not have expenditures in all three instances of the
 survey.
 For cases such as electricity in Tanzania, we in fact find the survey field
 for 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

main lighting fuel
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 more reliable for the test of electricity consumption than the last expenditure
 on electricity (note that kerosene is much cheaper than electricity in
 Tanzania).
 Such matters can be made worse in cases of expenditure where seasonality
 (time of the year) is also an important factor.
 To address the issue, therefore, we are careful not to draw any conclusions
 from a household's expenditure over the time-series (i.e.
 survey snapshots in 2008, 2010 and 2012) - but rely on the average expenditure
 over a collection of households (in a particular region etc.).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
RESULTS
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The goal of econometric analysis is to see how long-term status needs of
 the consumers - fulfilled with purchase of assets - a change that translates
 into an upward movement in status in our model - relate with the short-term
 needs fulfilled with expensive non-durable consumption.
 Much the way we were wary of claiming that consumption on items indicates
 perception of status hierarchies, we don't claim that the observed social
 mobility - recorded in this way - serves as a measure of how status is
 perceived in society.
 We compare the variation in the expensive non-durable consumption (ENDC)
 across occupation ranks, education and the assets owned across the two
 countries (see quantile regression results).
 We also inspect how the expenditure on purchase of permanent assets vs
 non-durable consumption differs amongst the identified social identities.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our model doesn't require that a consumer purchases a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

composite item
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of quality (see Deaton 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonQualityQuantityVariation,DeatonSurveyElasticities"

\end_inset

).
 Instead, we believe that quality is a concern for the researcher and not
 for the consumer - who merely exercises her choice given the set of products
 available in the market for given prices (see the clarification from Nelson
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "NelsonQualityQuantity"

\end_inset

).
 Since status would always be priced in the market, a status item would
 be always more expensive than the rest of the items which provide the same
 functionality (see Chao et al
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Chao1998"

\end_inset

 for substantiation of this argument).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the econometric methods, it has been demonstrated in the literature
 that additive functions are not enough for substitutability (see Deaton
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeatonEconConsumer"

\end_inset

).
 We use the dual-approach - most famously described in the AIDS method -
 and use a simple formulation of the cost-function to understand how a constrain
ed regression over the cross-section can tell us about the consumption across
 the population of consumers.
 Our conclusions rely on the elasticities obtained in this manner.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is clear that the medium assets are limited to the cities - and the household
s in the rural areas miss out on ownership of these assets.
 This corresponds to major differences in the life-styles between rural
 and urban areas in the developing countries.
 There are less opportunities for expensive non-durable consumption in the
 rural parts of Tanzania - except for marriage - where the expenditure seems
 proportionally high.
 The status is more likely to be derived from assets in the rural areas
 - compared to a more advanced economy such as that of South Africa.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of social identities and factors such as multiple wives are issues
 that we haven't covered - since a valid comparison of such social factors
 between the countries is out of scope of our study.
\end_layout

